B.a8u=new A.zt("What is the smallest unit of life?",B.a0O,1,"A cell is the smallest thing that is alive on its own.")
B.agR=new A.iA("What is a cell?","The smallest living building block of every living thing.","A cell is the smallest unit of life. That means it is the tiniest thing that is truly alive on its own. Think of a cell like a single brick. A house is built from many bricks, and in the same way your body is built from trillions of cells. Some living things, like bacteria, are just one single cell. Bigger living things, like plants, animals, and you, are made of many cells working together. Cells are far too small to see with your eyes, so scientists use a microscope to look at them.",B.Us,B.xd,B.a8u,"what is a cell biology for beginners",null,null)
B.ac2=new A.h6("Magnification","how many times bigger the image looks than the real thing")
B.WZ=s([B.ac2],t.fh)
B.R5=new A.jH("magnification = image size / actual size","Divide how big the picture is by how big the real object is. Example: if the image is 10 mm and the real cell is 1 mm, the magnification is 10 times.")
B.ZW=s([B.R5],t.mh)
B.a1T=s(["2 times","10 times","40 times","22 times"],t.s)
B.a8v=new A.zt("An image is 20 mm. The real cell is 2 mm. What is the magnification?",B.a1T,1,"20 divided by 2 equals 10, so it is 10 times bigger.")
B.agQ=new A.iA("Measuring cells (magnification)","Cells are tiny, so we use a microscope and a simple formula to measure how much bigger the image is.","Because cells are so small, we look at them through a microscope, which makes them appear much bigger. The number of times bigger the image looks is called the magnification. We can work it out with an easy formula: divide the size of the image by the real size of the object. If you keep the units the same, the answer tells you how many times the microscope enlarged the cell.",B.WZ,B.ZW,B.a8v,"microscope magnification formula explained",null,null)
B.ac5=new A.h6("Membrane","the outer wall that controls what goes in and out")
B.ac0=new A.h6("Nucleus","the control center that holds the DNA instructions")
B.ac4=new A.h6("Cytoplasm","the jelly inside where the work happens")
B.Ui=s([B.ac5,B.ac0,B.ac4],t.fh)
B.XN=s(["Membrane","Cytoplasm","Nucleus","Wall"],t.s)
B.a8w=new A.zt("Which part is the control center of the cell?",B.XN,2,"The nucleus holds the instructions and acts as the boss.")
B.Zu=s(["Water","Protein","Other"],t.s)
B.Vq=s([70,18,12],t.n)
B.NN=new A.RA("pie","What a cell is mostly made of (%)",B.Zu,B.Vq)
B.agS=new A.iA("Parts of a cell","The membrane, nucleus, and cytoplasm each have a clear job.","A cell has a few important parts, and each one has a job. The membrane is like a thin skin or wall around the cell. It decides what is allowed in and out. The nucleus is the control center, like the manager or boss, and it holds the instructions called DNA. The cytoplasm is the jelly that fills the cell, where most of the work happens and the parts float around.",B.Ui,B.xd,B.a8w,"parts of a cell explained simply",B.NN,null)
